O Eric Schmidt said: "With 'Google Gears' we are tackling a key limitation of the browser in order to make it a stronger platform for deploying all types of applications, and enabling a better user experience. "We believe strongly in the power of the community to stretch this new technology to the limits of what's possible, and ultimately emerge with an open standard that benefits everyone." According to various reports, Adobe Systems supports the new technology and is already developing its own version. Browser makers Mozilla and Opera were also said to be keen to get involved with Gears. The announcement coincided with Google Developer Day, which is taking place today at 10 cities around the world including Moscow, London, and Beijing where a whole range of Google products are being trumpeted by the firm. You can play around with the beta software which is available for Mac, Windows, and Linux users Post a new comment Internet Explorer for Linux ?! Track this type of story as a custom Atom/RSS feed or by email. Data protection watchdogs' letter to Google goes public It was Microsoft wot done it Google acquires 'sandbox' technology for secure browsing Google faces multiple privacy probes Google plays cat and mouse with regulators get to know you Microsoft too busy to name Linux patents Google's search dominance continues to grow Open Source may be cheap - but we still want support Microsoft launches no-code mashup tool Hotmail is dead! Long live Hotmail! The Microsoft Partner Program: Click to see your Map to Success Make IT run. Make IT safe. Run IT run. BigFix IT. Next is now! Microsoft&reg; Visual Studio 2005 Promote your Events and Training courses for free Get Started with Virtualization in 3 easy steps Try Sun servers, workstations and storage products free for 60-days Nortel is leading the evolution from TDM to IPT. Visit www.nortel.com/ipt123 The key to effective security Virus protection isn't just a Windows issue Top 10 Considerations When Choosing Server