level, allowing you to directly impact your cars performance for the first time as well as personalize its appearance. Need for Speed ProStreet is a true taste of raw adrenaline and racing with consequences. Every dent, every scratch and every crumpled body panel is a battle scar, proof of your commitment and competitive mettle. With an aggressive and skilled AI system, you become immersed in an unmatched believable race experience. Add in a revolutionary online mode that will redefine the meaning of competitive social play, and Need for Speed ProStreet is the ultimate formula for an emotionally charged street racing showdown. Need for Speed ProStreet will be available for Xbox 360 video game and entertainment system, PLAYSTATION®3 computer entertainment system, and Wii as well as the PlayStation®2 computer entertainment system, Nintendo DS, PSP® (PlayStation® Portable) handheld entertainment system, PC and mobile. More information can be found at www.needforspeed.com. Press can download assets at http://info.ea.com. Who's Online on WFC Spiderman The Movie 3 Danny Phantom : Urban Jungle My Animal Centre : In Africa YuGiOh! World Championship 2007 Wario Master of Disguise Lost In Blue 2 Pirates Of The Caribbean 3 FF Fables Chocobo Tales Pirates Of The Caribbean 3 Prince of Persia: Ri... All content, code and design is Copyright © 2000-2007 Vooks. All rights reserved. ABN 30 690 554 368 This Web site is not endorsed, sponsored, nor otherwise affiliated with Nintendo.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/13-6&fd=R&url=http://www.webpronews.com/topnews/2007/05/31/google-picks-up-panoramio&cid=1116827601&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Google Picks Up Panoramio | WebProNews Breaking eBusiness and Search News Google Picks Up Panoramio on Thu, 05/31/2007 - 08:39. Panoramio has worked hand in hand with Google for a long time, but, on Wednesday evening, the relationship became more of a hand within hand sort of thing as Google acquired the company. Panoramio &ldquo;is a website that enables digital photographers to geolocate, store and organize their photographs - and to view those photographs in Google Earth and Google Maps,&rdquo; as explained by a statement from Google. The acquisition won&rsquo;t change any of that; Panoramio will continue to be a default layer in Yet, presumably because of the privacy concerns that pop up whenever Google is involved, users are being provided with the opportunity to &ldquo;opt out&rdquo; of the acquisition. Users who don&rsquo;t choose this option - or who do nothing at all - will, at the close of the deal, have their Panoramio-related data and photos transferred to the search engine giant. The acquisition will, however, &ldquo;bring many advantages to Panoramio users, starting with a better infrastructure to improve the reliability of Panoramio, more frequent updates of Panoramio&rsquo;s Google Earth layer, and more resources for some invisible tasks that take time out from working on new features,&rdquo; according to &ldquo;Jos&eacute;, Joaqu&iacute;n and Eduardo&rdquo; - Panoramio&rsquo;s three . (Joaqu&iacute;n and Eduardo are actually co-founders.) One last note - even as the $75 million deal between eBay and StumbleUpon is confirmed, we&rsquo;ve been left in the dark about the financial details of the Google-Panoramio acquisition. The terms were not disclosed, but, according to , the company was &ldquo;very (and we mean very) happy&rdquo; about the takeover. Doug is a staff writer for for the