http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-2&fd=R&url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news%3Fpid%3D20601103%26sid%3DaGxLoaddlZoM%26refer%3Dus&cid=1116342796&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ , May 31 12:15 , May 31 17:15 , Jun 01 01:15 Australia & New Zealand Wayward California Whales May Have Returned to Ocean (Update3) By Vivek Shankar and Michael B. Marois May 30 (Bloomberg) -- Two humpback whales may have found their way back into the Pacific Ocean through San Francisco Bay after wandering off their migration path for more than two weeks. The mother and calf, dubbed Delta and Dawn, were last seen 8:30 p.m. yesterday within 5 miles (8.3 kilometers) of the Golden Gate Bridge. They may have slipped under the bridge overnight and into open sea, said Bernadette Fees, a deputy director with the California Department of Fish and Game. ``It is reasonable they&#39;ve made their way out,&#39;&#39; Fees said this evening. The duo, which wandered off course en route to Alaska, attracted crowds to the banks of the Sacramento River as they meandered upstream starting about May 13. After resisting efforts to drive them back south toward the ocean, the whales thrilled rescuers yesterday by crossing back into San Pablo Bay, just north of San Francisco Bay. ``We all cheered like, `Yay!&#39;&#39;&#39; Jim Oswald, a spokesman for the Marine Mammal Center, said yesterday in a telephone interview. ``It&#39;s been really exhilarating.&#39;&#39; Today probably marked the end of a weeks-long detour during which the whales traveled as far as 70 miles (112 kilometers) off course. By May 20, they had reached a dead end at the Port of Sacramento, northeast of San Francisco. They turned downriver, then spent more than a week stalled in fresh water. Their unwillingness to head back to the Pacific frustrated rescuers, who tried to drive the whales homeward. Scientists fired on the whales with water cannons, played sound recordings of an Orca feeding on a whale and even car- alarm noise to try to force them toward the ocean. Eventually, the whales headed downriver on their own. Marine biologists and veterinarians worried for the whales&#39; health as they lingered in the river. Both animals had cuts on their backs, probably from boat propellers, and they developed skin blisters from the fresh water. The whales were given injections of antibiotics to stave off infections. ``As far as letting nature take its own course and letting them die, I don&#39;t think that&#39;s an option because their injuries are a result of human activities,&#39;&#39; Frances Gulland, director of veterinary science at the Marine Mammal Center in Sausalito, said during a May 23 press briefing. ``We have some obligation to compensate for what we&#39;ve done to these animals.&#39;&#39; Humpback whales, which can live as long as 80 years and weigh as much as 30 tons, were hunted to near extinction until they were listed as an endangered species in the 1960s. There are less than 6,000 left in the Pacific Ocean, according to the Marine Mammal Center. The whales startled rescuers on May 27 by swimming more than 24 miles downstream, according to the U.S. Coast Guard. They moved south along the delta of the Sacramento River, California&#39;s largest, and entered bay waters yesterday. A flotilla of 12 boats accompanied them to offer protection from large ships, and to prevent the animals from turning back in the wrong direction. As the duo returned to saltier waters, their skin conditions improved, Oswald said. When the whales were marooned, crowds gathered at marinas in Rio Vista and the Port of Sacramento, trying to catch a glimpse of the 45-foot (13.7-meter) mother and the 25-foot calf. During the rescue effort, more than 2,600 suggestions from the public poured into a special e-mail account set up by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. One e-mail suggested using helicopters to harass the animals downriver, while another proposed building a fake whale with an outboard motor to lead them to the Pacific. A Navy dolphin squad might be able to guide the whales home, according to one e-mail. And a psychic asked to read the whales&#39; minds. ``There have been some real interesting folks who&#39;ve contacted us,&#39;&#39; Fees said. The rescue team included the Coast Guard, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration personnel, the state Department of Fish and Game and the Governor&#39;s Office of Emergency Services, as well as local law enforcement. To contact the reporters on this story: Vivek Shankar in San Francisco at ; Michael B. Marois in Sacramento at Last Updated: May 30, 2007 21:22 EDT Wachovia to Buy A.G. Edwards for $6.8 Billion, Doubling Brokerage Division Economy Expands at a 0.6 Percent Annual Rate, Weakest Pace in Four Years Home Prices in U.S. Climbed at Slowest Pace in Decade During First Quarter
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/5-3&fd=R&url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,276460,00.html&cid=1116342796&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Vignette StoryServer 5.0 Wed May 30 13:39:23 2007 FOXNews.com - Wayward Humpback Whales May Have Slipped Back Into Pacific - Science News | Current Articles We Report. You Decide. Search the Web with Vignette StoryServer 5.0 Wed May 30 14:28:53 2007 FOX News Election Coverage - Evolution and Paleontology - The Human Body Send news tip to FOXNews.com Wayward Humpback Whales May Have Slipped Back Into Pacific Wednesday, May 30, 2007 May 22: One of the two lost humpbacks slaps her tail on Sacramento River near Rio Vista, Calif. May 22: One of the two lost humpbacks slaps her tail on Sacramento River near Rio Vista, Calif. SAN FRANCISCO &#151; Two lost seen just before sunset Tuesday nearing their ocean home after a two-week sojourn through inland waterways may have slipped back into the Pacific overnight. Rescuers launched several boats in an effort to find the mother humpback and her calf Wednesday morning, but have not spotted the whales, said Bernadette Fees, deputy director of the California Department of Fish and Game "If they have gone out and made their way past the Golden Gate, they have done so quietly," Fees said. &#8226; Click here to visit FOXNews.com's Natural Science Center. The pair were last seen Tuesday night less than 10 miles from the Golden Gate after they passed under another busy bridge and entered The whales passed under the Richmond-San Rafael Bridge on Tuesday afternoon, the last bridge along the pair's route before reaching the Golden Gate. If the humpbacks were able navigate south around Marin County's Tiburon Peninsula and nearby Angel Island, few obstacles would have been left on their route past Alcatraz to the Pacific Ocean. Wayward Humpback Whales Make It Back to San Francisco Bay Wayward Whales Make Good Progress Back Toward Pacific Lost Humpback Whales to Be Sprayed With Fire Hoses Orca Sounds Fail to Scare Wayward Whales Downstream Lost Humpback Whales Still Swimming in Circles Lost Humpback Whales Swim in Circles in California River Wayward Humpback Whales Start Heading Downriver Humpbacks Make Move Back to Pacific Ocean Taped Whale Songs Fail to Lure Humpbacks Back to Pacific Biologists Try to Lure Wayward Whales Back to Pacific Two Humpback Whales Head Up California River Rescuers planned to rely on commercial vessels and Coast Guard patrols on regular duty to spot the pair, which have been easily sighted throughout their inland journey, if they were still hiding in the bay. Authorities sent several boats west of the Golden Gate to try to confirm the whales had returned to the ocean, officials said. "The assumption is if we have not sighted the mother and calf by late afternoon that they have made their way out to the Pacific," Fees said. The duo was first spotted May 13 and got as far as 90 miles inland to the Port of Sacramento before turning around. Biologists originally had planned to attach a satellite tracking tag to the mother humpback, but gusty winds and malfunctioning equipment stymied that effort. Despite the apparently anticlimactic end to the humpbacks' saga, which has attracted thousands to Northern California waterfronts, biologists said the chance to closely observe the pair for so long was invaluable for science. "While they may have gone on their way, we still have the benefit of all the information we haven't had access to before," Fees said. "If we learned anything about these two, it is that they will do what they do when they want to do it." Ariadne Green, 57, of Vallejo, was one of many who came to catch what may have been a final glimpse of the pair Tuesday after traveling last week to Rio Vista, where the whales circled for a week before heading ocean-ward. She described the humpbacks' inland visit as a "profound spiritual experience" but was equally grateful for their departure. "They need to go home now because their health is in jeopardy," Green said. "It's good to know they're on their way back." Biologists said the saltier water where the mother humpback whale and her calf had been swimming since leaving Rio Vista helped reverse some of the health problems caused by long exposure to fresh water. Lesions that had formed on the humpbacks' skin over the weekend appeared to be sloughing off, Fees said. Scientists also reported that a coating of algae that was clinging to the mother farther upriver had fallen away. Recent photographs showed that serious wounds suffered by both whales also had appeared to begin healing, said Rod McInnis, a spokesman for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration Antibiotics were injected into the whales on Saturday to try to slow the damage from the gashes, likely from a boat's keel. A convoy of boats had been escorting the pair to protect them from heavy ship traffic in the bay. See Next Story in Science Vignette StoryServer 5.0 Thu May 31 10:58:34 2007 Vignette StoryServer 5.0 Thu May 31 10:29:30 2007 Wildlife expert Jack Hanna on rash of coyote attacks Latest Fox News Headlines Jack Hanna on rash of coyote attacks Major draught threatens Florida waters Efforts continue to help wayward whales Wal-Mart Cashier Says He Was Fired Over MySpace Bomb Joke 'Guru of Ganja' Convicted on Marijuana Charges To Have and to Hold: How Stars Stay Happily Hitched Iowa Woman Sues Wal-Mart Over Fall in Puddle of Vomit Notorious Spam King Nabbed in Seattle, Could Face Long Prison Term Son Nearly Amputates Mom's Arm With Samurai Sword, Police Say Pop Tarts: Naked Britney Spears Billboard Banned in New Zealand Man Described as One of World's Top 10 Spammers Arrested in Seattle Two Years After Disappearance, Natalee Holloway's Mom Remains 'Hopeful' U.S. Marine Vet Faces Hearing on Discharge Status for Wearing Uniform at Protest Authorities Believe Religious Differences Played Role in Slaying of California Father, Daughter Spain Makes Court Claim Over Sunken Colon