http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/2-0&fd=R&url=http://arstechnica.com/journals/apple.ars/2007/05/31/steve-and-bill-reminisce-at-d-all-things-digital&cid=1116799532&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Steve and Bill reminisce at D: All Things Digital Steve and Bill reminisce at D: All Things Digital | Published: 09:59AM CT Steve Jobs and Bill Gates at D: All Things Digital Those expecting fireworks during the of Steve and Bill at D: All Things Digital will likely be disappointed. Most of the 90-minute interview was spent talking about the "good old days" in Silicon Valley and vague prognostications on the future. That, and a game of reciprocative back-patting. Still, there were a few interesting bits of information for amateur Appleologists on the Internet. The conference began with a question about what each had contributed to the computer industry, to which Gates complimented Jobs&#39; taste and sense of aesthetics. At this point, the conversation devolved into Silicon Valley "war story" material about how many "K" this piece of technology had, though Gates got a laugh with his opening comment about not being Fake Steve Jobs. Jobs&#39; first interesting comment came in response to a question about the relationship between Apple and Microsoft in 1997. If the game was a zero-sum game where if Apple wanted to win, Microsoft had to lose, then Apple was going to lose. But Apple didn&rsquo;t have to beat Microsoft. It had to remember what Apple was. At this point, the latest Mac and PC ads came up, and Jobs made a short nonpology. The art of those commercials is not to be mean, but for the guys to like each other. The PC Guy is great... The PC Guy is what makes it all work. Again, Gates was funny, replying that "PC guy&rsquo;s mother loves him." Shortly thereafter, Steve Jobs said that that "Apple views itself as a software company." All the hardware Apple makes, the Mac, the iPod, and soon the iPhone, is nothing more than a "box" to run the software. The is a fascinating insight into the vision of Steve Jobs, and a little disconcerting to me. First, Apple makes most of its money from selling "boxes." More importantly, while that hardware may be nothing special inside, Apple has always striven for unmatched industrial design on the outside. This is not to say that Apple is getting out of the hardware business, though. Jobs put to rest any conspiracy pinhead theory about Apple doing that when talking about personal technology in the next five to ten years. The PC has been very resilient. Its death has been predicted many times. But the Internet came around and invigorated it. And then it plateaued again. And then digital media came around and invigorated it again. And so I think the PC is going to continue to be with us. Finally, there was an item of great interest to those of us who have suffered with .Mac, which apparently must include tech guru Walt Mossberg. In response to a very restrained point about "not developing .Mac" since its inception, Jobs was surprisingly candid. I couldn&#39;t agree more, and we&#39;ll make up for lost time in the near future. One can only hope. Overall, the interview is pretty tame. I strongly recommend this for those wanting to watch Bill and Steve. Japanese PS3s blessed with new fighting games in the PlayStation Store While it can be weeks between good releases on the American PlayStation Store, Japanese gamers get a solid update of PSone games today. The Mozilla Manifesto: with great power comes great responsibility Sellers running scared: a look inside the world of AllOfMP3 vouchers Linksys iPhone CIT400: a Skype phone without OS limits What the Copyright Office thinks about Fair Use Apple TV just found its killer app How big is your (business) internet pipe? Tom's Benchmarks 'Budget Box' with GeForce 8800GTX Record industry cartel wins the right to screw UK consumers MPAA: We are committed to fair use, interoperability, and DRM Project aims to bring DX10 gaming to XP, Linux, OS X The Daylight Sa