ial trailer ( which you can find here ) but now EA has released the first batch of screens. According to EA ProStreet boasts "impeccable precision and impressively detailed photo-realistic graphics". It also features "Autosculpt" technology which will directly impact the car's performance after a bust-up with racing rivals. Every dent, every scratch and every crumpled body panel is a battle scar, proof of your commitment and competitive mettle, says EA. "Need for Speed ProStreet accelerates street racing culture by providing the ultimate stage for the pursuit of street racing supremacy," said Executive Producer, Larry LaPierre. "This is a game about building the ultimate performance-tuned battle machine, taking it to multi-disciplinary showdowns all over the world and pitting your skills and reputation against the very best street racers." Check out the new screens and we'll have more soon. Read all 1 comments 1 / 5 Screenshots New Need For Speed shots roar into view Need For Speed: Pro Street - first footage and details MGS4 not confirmed for 360 PSP firmware updated for new PS3 features Hackers break 360 lockout Ubisoft admits its Wii "mistakes" MUST SEE Bioshock gameplay trailer New Need For Speed shots roar into view New Halo maps and vehicles revealed First Guitar Hero 3 footage rocks the 'net &copy; Future Publishing Limited. Reg No. 2008885 England. 30 Monmouth Street, Bath, BA1 2BW.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18-5&fd=R&url=http://www.theinquirer.net/default.aspx%3Farticle%3D39906&cid=1116773880&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Toshiba kills off Intel deal The unofficial home of AMD fanboys Thursday +44 208 248 2800 To advertise in Europe To advertise in Asia To advertise in North America Join the INQbot Mail List for a weekly guide to our news stories: Toshiba kills off Intel deal Tuesday 29 May 2007, 08:47 ended a six year monogamous relationship cuddling up to Chipzilla and will have a fling with AMD. The outfit, which is the fourth-largest maker of notebook computers has said that it will end the exclusive agreement it has had with Intel since 2001. The company said it will stick AMD chips in 20 per cent of laptop models sold in the US and Europe. , the reason for the change is a reduction in procurement costs. Toshiba wants to have cheaper laptops in the shops by Christmas. A shift to AMD chips could lead to a 10 per cent drop in the costs of parts, Discuss on our Forum 1. AMD's Hector goes on safari 2. Bare naked case gets thorough testing 3. QX6850 quad Kentsfield sighted in the wild 4. GDDR4 coming to 2900XT, apparently 5. US spam king faces up to 65 years in clink &#169; 2007 VNU Business Publications Ltd.
http://news.google.com/news/url?sa=T&ct=us/18i-0&fd=R&url=http://www.earthtimes.org/articles/show/67287.html&cid=1116773880&ei=muxeRqqvDIX20AHe4M3QDQ Toshiba plumps for AMD chips in its laptops Toshiba plumps for AMD chips in its laptops Tue, 29 May 2007 15:02:00GMT In an announcement that is bound to affect Intel Corp quite badly, Toshiba Corp said that it would be providing microprocessors developed by Advanced Micro Devices Inc (AMD), ending the exclusive contract with Intel. Toshiba revealed that it would be shipping out AMD processors in at least 20 percent of its notebooks sold in United States and Europe. Company spokeswoman Yuko Sugahara said that Toshiba would be including AMD processors in moderate-priced standard models for both individual and corporate clients. Analysts believe that the move comes on the backdrop of intense pressure on Toshiba to compete against its rivals, Fujitsu Ltd. and NEC Corp, both of which make use of chips produced by Intel and AMD. While the last fiscal year saw Toshiba's PC revenues increase by 14 percent, the operating margins remain below the 1 percent mark in that particular area. Sugahara said that the company decided to include AMD processors in its computers following rising "consumer demand" and "favorable terms from suppliers". Analysts see this move as a start of the end of Intel's domination in the chip market. "This could be a message that an era in which Intel took the lion's share of microprocessor profits as the king of PC chips is over. With PCs becoming commodity products, there seems to be a new way of thinking that competition should be introduced even in procurement of such core parts like processors as long as there are no major differences in product specifications", said Yoshihiro Shimada, an analyst at Macquarie Securities. Toshiba is hoping to incorporate AMD chips in some machines so as to reduce its parts cost by at least 10 percent. Copyright &copy; 2007 Respective Author Email this article (Click He